   <mods:abstract>Prior audit research and PCAOB inspection reports provide evidence that auditors often fail to revise audit plans to effectively address new risks that are revealed during audit fieldwork. I investigate how budget performance measures contribute to this issue by increasing both auditors' perceived and actual resource pressures. I also examine how a psychology intervention called constraint-based planning (CBP) encourages auditors to allocate their resources more effectively in an environment where audit risk is shifting. I incorporate the economic incentives and resource constraints of an audit into an experimental economics experiment to test my research questions. I find that budget performance measures cause auditors to misallocate their resources when the perceived or actual level of audit risk shifts after the creation of the budget. I also find that auditors who participate in CBP allocate their resources more effectively to an extent that they are more likely to address accounts that change in riskiness.</mods:abstract>
